<HEAD>GENERAL CONTENTS.</HEAD>
<LIST>
<ITEM><HI>Page</HI> 1. THANKFUL acknowledgment of those that have written and testified against slavery&mdash; 3. Some reflexions and apology for advancing these Thoughts and Sentiments&mdash;5. Some account of the Au|thor's captivity&mdash;11. Reflexions on his deliverance from Grenada&mdash;13. Thanks to God and his good Providence for the great advantages of the Bible.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Page</HI> 14. General observations on the Cursory Re|marker, an advocate for slavery&mdash;21. Sundry pretences for enslaving the Africans answered&mdash;23. False conse|quences as some good arising from slavery exploded &mdash;24. Almost nothing to be seen abroad among christians but ruffians and barbarians&mdash;25. Some account of the slave-procurers&mdash;27. That the Africans sell their wives and children, nothing can be more contrary to their natural feelings, and absurd.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Page</HI> 29. Observations on other grand pretences made use of by the favourers of slavery refuted&mdash;31. Different complexions and features among men as being natural to different climates and situations&mdash;32. Concerning Cain, and the notion of some mark set upon him&mdash;33. Con|cerning the prediction and curse which took place in the lineage of Canaan&mdash;36. Of Africa chiefly peopled by the descendants of Ham&mdash;38. That slavery was an ancient custom, but never lawful.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Page</HI> 40. Another part of the grand pretence for en|slaving men considered as admitted into the law by Moses, and the case of the Canaanites, who were reduced to a poor and menial employment, equal to the state of la|bourers
<PB N="ii" REF="4">
in any free country&mdash;43. State of bond servants admitted for great and wise purposes, but not contrary to the natural rights and liberties of men&mdash;45. Allegorical use of different complexions and other things, as men|tioned in sacred writ, intended for something else than only being eligible in the variety of the scale of nature&mdash; 47. Another form of instruction for men considered by the state of bondage mentioned in the law&mdash;50. Allego|rical use of the wars of the Israelites, &amp;c.&mdash;53. Conclu|sion, that no slavery can be lawful.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Page</HI> 54. Observations on various perversions of sacred writ made use of by the favourers of slavery, to embolden themselves in wickedness; and other historical precedents made use of to encourage slavery and extirpation, shewn to be unwarrantable and highly absurd.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Page</HI> 59. Observation on the brutish stupidity of men in general&mdash;60. Laws of God considered against slavery, and that the enslavers of men are the servants of the devil&mdash;62. Unlawfulness of slavery, and the European traffic in it only piracy&mdash;63. Contrary to the law of our Lord Christ&mdash;64. All the dealers of slaves guilty of death according to the righteous law of God; and if they do not repent, they must lie under their crimes for ever.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Page</HI> 66. All the criminal laws of civilization ought to be founded upon the law of God; and the breakers of that law, in many cases, ought to be enslaved, and those that break the laws of civilization, are the only men that others have any right to enslave, because they sell them|selves to work iniquity.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Page</HI> 73. Every slaveholder is a robber, if he buys a man without his own consent, or by any fraudulent me|thod to obtain his consent unawares; and it is the duty of every man to deliver himself from rogues and villains if he can.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Page</HI> 74. Historical observations, and the case of the Africans considered.</ITEM>
